 Koninkrijk","Trelawney, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Truro, Cornwall, England":"Truro, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"about 1265–1308":"about 1265–1308","1265–1308":"1265–1308","1260–1308":"1260–1308","1295–1334":"1295–1334","1248–1274":"1248–1274","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","before 1265":"before 1265","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1215":"1295","1248":"1248","1334":"1334","1265":"1265","before 1295":"before 1295","about 1265":"about 1265","1308":"1308","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, UK":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Trelawney, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Truro, Cornwall, England":"Truro, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane de Trewynick was born about 1265, in Truro, Cornwall, England, her father, Stephen Trewynick, was 18 and her mother, Isabel Bottrell, was 16. She married William de Trelony before 1295, in Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1308, in Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1265–1308":"umbes 1265–1308","1265–1308":"1265–1308","1260–1308":"1260–1308","1295–1334":"1295–1334","1248–1274":"1248–1274","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","before 1265":"enne 1265","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1215":"1295","1248":"1248","1334":"1334","1265":"1265","before 1295":"enne 1295","about 1265":"umbes 1265","1308":"1308","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, UK":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, 